# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: secure-random-generation
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] This article provides a simple model to follow when implementing solutions to protect data at rest.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Passwords should not be stored using reversible encryption - secure password hashing algorithms should be used instead.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] The Password Storage Cheat Sheet contains further guidance on storing passwords.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] The first step in designing any application is to consider the overall architecture of the system, as this will have a huge impact on the technical implementation.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] This process should begin with considering the threat model of the application (i.e, who you are trying to protect that data against).
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Note that many cloud environments provide these services, so these should be taken advantage of where possible.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] The Secrets Management Cheat Sheet contains further guidance on this topic.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Which layer(s) are most appropriate will depend on the threat model.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] For example, hardware level encryption is effective at protecting against the physical theft of the server, but will provide no protection if an attacker is able to compromise the server remotely.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] The best way to protect sensitive information is to not store it in the first place.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Although this applies to all kinds of information, it is most often applicable to credit card details, as they are highly desirable for attackers, and PCI DSS has such stringent requirements for how they must be stored.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Wherever possible, the storage of sensitive information should be avoided.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] For symmetric encryption **AES** with a key that's at least **128 bits** (ideally **256 bits**) and a secure mode should be used as the preferred algorithm.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] For asymmetric encryption, use elliptical curve cryptography (ECC) with a secure curve such as **Curve25519** as a preferred algorithm.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] If ECC is not available and **RSA** must be used, then ensure that the key is at least **2048 bits**.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Many other symmetric and asymmetric algorithms are available which have their own pros and cons, and they may be better or worse than AES or Curve25519 in specific use cases.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] In some cases there may be regulatory requirements that limit the algorithms that can be used, such as FIPS 140-2 or PCI DSS.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] There are various modes that can be used to allow block ciphers (such as AES) to encrypt arbitrary amounts of data, in the same way that a stream cipher would.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] These modes have different security and performance characteristics, and a full discussion of them is outside the scope of this cheat sheet.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Some of the modes have requirements to generate secure initialisation vectors (IVs) and other attributes, but these should be handled automatically by the library.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Where available, authenticated modes should always be used.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] These provide guarantees of the integrity and authenticity of the data, as well as confidentiality.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] The most commonly used authenticated modes are **GCM** and **CCM**, which should be used as a first preference.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] If GCM or CCM are not available, then CTR mode or CBC mode should be used.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] As these do not provide any guarantees about the authenticity of the data, separate authentication should be implemented, such as using the Encrypt-then-MAC technique.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] ECB should not be used outside of very specific circumstances.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] For RSA, it is essential to enable Random Padding.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Random Padding is also known as OAEP or Optimal Asymmetric Encryption Padding.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] This class of defense protects against Known Plain Text Attacks by adding randomness at the beginning of the payload.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] The Padding Schema of PKCS#1 is typically used in this case.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Random numbers (or strings) are needed for various security critical functionality, such as generating encryption keys, IVs, session IDs, CSRF tokens or password reset tokens.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] As such, it is important that these are generated securely, and that it is not possible for an attacker to guess and predict them.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] It is generally not possible for computers to generate truly random numbers (without special hardware), so most systems and languages provide two different types of randomness.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Pseudo-Random Number Generators (PRNG) provide low-quality randomness that are much faster, and can be used for non-security related functionality (such as ordering results on a page, or randomising UI elements).
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] However, they **must not** be used for anything security critical, as it is often possible for attackers to guess or predict the output.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Cryptographically Secure Pseudo-Random Number Generators (CSPRNG) are designed to produce a much higher quality of randomness (more strictly, a greater amount of entropy), making them safe to use for security-sensitive functionality.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] However, they are slower and more CPU intensive, can end up blocking in some circumstances when large amounts of random data are requested.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] As such, if large amounts of non-security related randomness are needed, they may not be appropriate.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] The table below shows the recommended algorithms for each language, as well as insecure functions that should not be used.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Universally unique identifiers (UUIDs or GUIDs) are sometimes used as a quick way to generate random strings.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Although they can provide a reasonable source of randomness, this will depend on the type or version of the UUID that is created.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Specifically, version 1 UUIDs are comprised of a high precision timestamp and the MAC address of the system that generated them, so are **not random** (although they may be hard to guess, given the timestamp is to the nearest 100ns).
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Type 4 UUIDs are randomly generated, although whether this is done using a CSPRNG will depend on the implementation.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Unless this is known to be secure in the specific language or framework, the randomness of UUIDs should not be relied upon.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Applications should be designed to still be secure even if cryptographic controls fail.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Any information that is stored in an encrypted form should also be protected by additional layers of security.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Application should also not rely on the security of encrypted URL parameters, and should enforce strong access control to prevent unauthorised access to information.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Keys should be randomly generated using a cryptographically secure function, such as those discussed in the Secure Random Number Generation section.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Keys **should not** be based on common words or phrases, or on "random" characters generated by mashing the keyboard.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Where multiple keys are used (such as data separate data-encrypting and key-encrypting keys), they should be fully independent from each other.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Once one of these criteria have been met, a new key should be generated and used for encrypting any new data.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Marking each item with the ID of the key that was used to encrypt it, and storing multiple keys to allow the old data to be decrypted.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] The first option should generally be preferred, as it greatly simplifies both the application code and key management processes; however, it may not always be feasible.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Note that old keys should generally be stored for a certain period after they have been retired, in case old backups of copies of the data need to be decrypted.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] It is important that the code and processes required to rotate a key are in place **before** they are required, so that keys can be quickly rotated in the event of a compromise.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Additionally, processes should also be implemented to allow the encryption algorithm or library to be changed, in case a new vulnerability is found in the algorithm or implementation.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Securely storing cryptographic keys is one of the hardest problems to solve, as the application always needs to have some level of access to the keys in order to decrypt the data.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] While it may not be possible to fully protect the keys from an attacker who has fully compromised the application, a number of steps can be taken to make it harder for them to obtain the keys.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Where available, the secure storage mechanisms provided by the operating system, framework or cloud service provider should be used.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] There are many advantages to using these types of secure storage over simply putting keys in configuration files.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] In some cases none of these will be available, such as in a shared hosting environment, meaning that it is not possible to obtain a high degree of protection for any encryption keys.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] The Secrets Management Cheat Sheet provides more details on securely storing secrets.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Where possible, encryption keys should be stored in a separate location from encrypted data.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] For example, if the data is stored in a database, the keys should be stored in the filesystem.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] This means that if an attacker only has access to one of these (for example through directory traversal or SQL injection), they cannot access both the keys and the data.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Depending on the architecture of the environment, it may be possible to store the keys and data on separate systems, which would provide a greater degree of isolation.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Where possible, encryption keys should themselves be stored in an encrypted form.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] For this to be effective, the KEK must be stored separately from the DEK.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] The encrypted DEK can be stored with the data, but will only be usable if an attacker is able to also obtain the KEK, which is stored on another system.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] The KEK should also be at least as strong as the DEK.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] The envelope encryption guidance from Google contains further details on how to manage DEKs and KEKs.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] In simpler application architectures (such as shared hosting environments) where the KEK and DEK cannot be stored separately, there is limited value to this approach, as an attacker is likely to be able to obtain both of the keys at the same time.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] However, it can provide an additional barrier to unskilled attackers.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] A key derivation function (KDF) could be used to generate a KEK from user-supplied input (such a passphrase), which would then be used to encrypt a randomly generated DEK.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] This allows the KEK to be easily changed (when the user changes their passphrase), without needing to re-encrypt the data (as the DEK remains the same).
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographically-secure-pseudorandom-number-generator] A **cryptographically secure pseudorandom number generator** (**CSPRNG**) or **cryptographic pseudorandom number generator** (**CPRNG**) is a pseudorandom number generator (PRNG) with properties that make it suitable for use in cryptography.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographically-secure-pseudorandom-number-generator] It is also referred to as a **cryptographic random number generator** (**CRNG**).
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographically-secure-pseudorandom-number-generator] The "quality" of the randomness required for these applications varies.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographically-secure-pseudorandom-number-generator] For example, creating a nonce in some protocols needs only uniqueness.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographically-secure-pseudorandom-number-generator] On the other hand, the generation of a master key requires a higher quality, such as more entropy.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographically-secure-pseudorandom-number-generator] And in the case of one-time pads, the information-theoretic guarantee of perfect secrecy only holds if the key material comes from a true random source with high entropy, and thus just any kind of pseudorandom number generator is insufficient.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographically-secure-pseudorandom-number-generator] Ideally, the generation of random numbers in CSPRNGs uses entropy obtained from a high-quality source, generally the operating system's randomness API.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographically-secure-pseudorandom-number-generator] However, unexpected correlations have been found in several such ostensibly independent processes.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographically-secure-pseudorandom-number-generator] From an information-theoretic point of view, the amount of randomness, the entropy that can be generated, is equal to the entropy provided by the system.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographically-secure-pseudorandom-number-generator] But sometimes, in practical situations, numbers are needed with more randomness than the available entropy can provide.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographically-secure-pseudorandom-number-generator] Also, the processes to extract randomness from a running system are slow in actual practice.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographically-secure-pseudorandom-number-generator] In such instances, a CSPRNG can sometimes be used.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographically-secure-pseudorandom-number-generator] A CSPRNG can "stretch" the available entropy over more bits.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographically-secure-pseudorandom-number-generator] The requirements of an ordinary PRNG are also satisfied by a cryptographically secure PRNG, but the reverse is not true.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographically-secure-pseudorandom-number-generator] For most PRNGs, when their state has been revealed, all past random numbers can be retrodicted, allowing an attacker to read all past messages, as well as future ones.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographically-secure-pseudorandom-number-generator] CSPRNGs are designed explicitly to resist this type of cryptanalysis.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographically-secure-pseudorandom-number-generator] There is an equivalent characterization: For any function family $G_{k}\colon \{{\texttt {0}},{\texttt {1}}\}^{k}\to \{{\texttt {0}},{\texttt {1}}\}^{p(k)}$ , G is a PRNG if and only if the next output bit of G cannot be predicted by a polynomial time algorithm.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographically-secure-pseudorandom-number-generator] Any PRNG $G\colon \{{\texttt {0}},{\texttt {1}}\}^{k}\to \{{\texttt {0}},{\texttt {1}}\}^{p(k)}$ can be turned into a forward secure PRNG with block length $p(k)-k$ by splitting its output into the next state and the actual output.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographically-secure-pseudorandom-number-generator] This is done by setting $G(s)=G_{\texttt {0}}(s)\Vert G_{\texttt {1}}(s)$ , in which $|G_{\texttt {0}}(s)|=|s|=k$ and $|G_{\texttt {1}}(s)|=p(k)-k$ ; then G is a forward secure PRNG with $G_{\texttt {0}}$ as the next state and $G_{\texttt {1}}$ as the pseudorandom output block of the current period.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographically-secure-pseudorandom-number-generator] Santha and Vazirani proved that several bit streams with weak randomness can be combined to produce a higher-quality, quasi-random bit stream.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographically-secure-pseudorandom-number-generator] Even earlier, John von Neumann suggested a simple algorithm that can remove a considerable amount of the bias in any bit stream.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographically-secure-pseudorandom-number-generator] "Practical" CSPRNG schemes not only include an CSPRNG algorithm, but also a way to initialize ("seed") it while keeping the seed secret.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographically-secure-pseudorandom-number-generator] Obviously, the technique is easily generalized to any block cipher; AES has been suggested.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographically-secure-pseudorandom-number-generator] If the key *k* is leaked, the entire X9.17 stream can be predicted; this weakness is cited as a reason for creating Yarrow.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographically-secure-pseudorandom-number-generator] All these above-mentioned schemes, save for X9.17, also mix the state of a CSPRNG with an additional source of entropy.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographically-secure-pseudorandom-number-generator] They are therefore not "pure" pseudorandom number generators, in the sense that the output is not completely determined by their initial state.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographically-secure-pseudorandom-number-generator] This addition aims to prevent attacks even if the initial state is compromised.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographically-secure-pseudorandom-number-generator] The third PRNG in this standard, CTR DRBG, is based on a block cipher running in counter mode.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographically-secure-pseudorandom-number-generator] It has an uncontroversial design but has been proven to be weaker in terms of distinguishing attack, than the security level of the underlying block cipher when the number of bits output from this PRNG is greater than two to the power of the underlying block cipher's block size in bits.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographically-secure-pseudorandom-number-generator] When the maximum number of bits output from this PRNG is equal to the 2blocksize, the resulting output delivers the mathematically expected security level that the key size would be expected to generate, but the output is shown to not be indistinguishable from a true random number generator.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographically-secure-pseudorandom-number-generator] When the maximum number of bits output from this PRNG is less than it, the expected security level is delivered and the output appears to be indistinguishable from a true random number generator.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographically-secure-pseudorandom-number-generator] It is noted in the next revision that the claimed security strength for CTR_DRBG depends on limiting the total number of generate requests and the bits provided per generate request.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographically-secure-pseudorandom-number-generator] The fourth and final PRNG in this standard is named Dual EC DRBG.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographically-secure-pseudorandom-number-generator] It has been shown to not be cryptographically secure and is believed to have a kleptographic NSA backdoor.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographically-secure-pseudorandom-number-generator] This is essentially NIST SP 800-90A with Dual_EC_DRBG removed, and is the withdrawn standard's replacement.
[src:secure-random-generation/cryptographically-secure-pseudorandom-number-generator] During World War II, Japan used a cipher machine for diplomatic communications; the United States was able to crack it and read its messages, mostly because the "key values" used were insufficiently random.
[src:secure-random-generation/dev-random] In Unix-like operating systems, **/dev/random** and **/dev/urandom** are special files that provide random numbers from a cryptographically secure pseudorandom number generator (CSPRNG).
[src:secure-random-generation/dev-random] The CSPRNG is seeded with entropy (a value that provides randomness) from environmental noise, collected from device drivers and other sources.
[src:secure-random-generation/dev-random] Users can obtain random numbers from the CSPRNG simply by reading the file.
[src:secure-random-generation/dev-random] Not all operating systems implement the same methods for /dev/random and /dev/urandom.
[src:secure-random-generation/dev-random] When entropy available is low, /dev/random will block; on newer systems, this typically happens at program startup until entropy is sufficient, before permanently unblocking.
[src:secure-random-generation/dev-random] The /dev/urandom device typically was never a blocking device, even if the pseudorandom number generator seed was not fully initialized with entropy since boot.
[src:secure-random-generation/dev-random] This special file originated in Linux in 1994.
[src:secure-random-generation/dev-random] It was quickly adopted by other Unix-like operating systems.
[src:secure-random-generation/dev-random] The Linux kernel provides the separate device files /dev/random and /dev/urandom.
[src:secure-random-generation/dev-random] Since kernel version 5.6 of 2020, /dev/random only blocks when the CSPRNG hasn't initialized.
[src:secure-random-generation/dev-random] Once initialized, /dev/random and /dev/urandom behave the same.
[src:secure-random-generation/dev-random] In October 2016, with the release of Linux kernel version 4.8, the kernel's /dev/urandom was switched over to a ChaCha20-based cryptographic pseudorandom number generator (CPRNG) implementation by Theodore Ts'o, based on Bernstein's well-regarded stream cipher ChaCha20.
[src:secure-random-generation/dev-random] Since version 5.17 of the Linux kernel, the random number generator switched from using the SHA-1 cryptographic hash function in the entropy collector to BLAKE2s, a newer, faster and more secure hash function.
[src:secure-random-generation/dev-random] Random number generation in kernel space was implemented for the first time for Linux in 1994 by Theodore Ts'o.
[src:secure-random-generation/dev-random] The implementation used secure hashes rather than ciphers, to avoid cryptography export restrictions that were in place when the generator was originally designed.
[src:secure-random-generation/dev-random] The implementation was also designed with the assumption that any given hash or cipher might eventually be found to be weak, and so the design is durable in the face of any such weaknesses.
[src:secure-random-generation/dev-random] Fast recovery from pool compromise is not considered a requirement, because the requirements for pool compromise are sufficient for much easier and more direct attacks on unrelated parts of the operating system.
[src:secure-random-generation/dev-random] In Ts'o's implementation, the generator keeps an estimate of the number of bits of noise in the entropy pool.
[src:secure-random-generation/dev-random] From this entropy pool random numbers are created.
[src:secure-random-generation/dev-random] When read, the /dev/random device will only return random bytes within the estimated number of bits of noise in the entropy pool.
[src:secure-random-generation/dev-random] When the entropy pool is empty, reads from /dev/random will block until additional environmental noise is gathered.
[src:secure-random-generation/dev-random] The intent is to serve as a cryptographically secure pseudorandom number generator, delivering output with entropy as large as possible.
[src:secure-random-generation/dev-random] This is suggested by the authors for use in generating cryptographic keys for high-value or long-term protection.
[src:secure-random-generation/dev-random] A counterpart to /dev/random is /dev/urandom ("unlimited"/non-blocking random source) which reuses the internal pool to produce more pseudo-random bits.
[src:secure-random-generation/dev-random] This means that the call will not block, but the output may contain less entropy than the corresponding read from /dev/random.
[src:secure-random-generation/dev-random] However such an attack is unlikely to come into existence, because once the entropy pool is unpredictable it doesn't leak security by a reduced number of bits.
[src:secure-random-generation/dev-random] It is also possible to write to /dev/random.
[src:secure-random-generation/dev-random] This allows any user to mix random data into the pool.
[src:secure-random-generation/dev-random] Non-random data is harmless, because only a privileged user can issue the ioctl needed to increase the entropy estimate.
[src:secure-random-generation/dev-random] The current amount of entropy and the size of the Linux kernel entropy pool, both measured in bits, are available in /proc/sys/kernel/random/ and can be displayed by the command `cat /proc/sys/kernel/random/entropy_avail` and `cat /proc/sys/kernel/random/poolsize` respectively.
[src:secure-random-generation/dev-random] Gutterman, Pinkas, & Reinman in March 2006 published a detailed cryptographic analysis of the Linux random number generator in which they describe several weaknesses.
[src:secure-random-generation/dev-random] Perhaps the most severe issue they report is with embedded or Live CD systems, such as routers and diskless clients, for which the bootup state is predictable and the available supply of entropy from the environment may be limited.
[src:secure-random-generation/dev-random] For a system with non-volatile memory, they recommend saving some state from the RNG at shutdown so that it can be included in the RNG state on the next reboot.
[src:secure-random-generation/dev-random] This issue, they note, is particularly critical in the case of a wireless router whose network traffic can be captured from a distance, and which may be using the RNG to generate keys for data encryption.
[src:secure-random-generation/dev-random] The Linux kernel provides support for several hardware random number generators, should they be installed.
[src:secure-random-generation/dev-random] The raw output of such a device may be obtained from /dev/hwrng.
[src:secure-random-generation/dev-random] With Linux kernel 3.16 and newer, the kernel itself mixes data from hardware random number generators into /dev/random on a sliding scale based on the definable entropy estimation quality of the HWRNG.
[src:secure-random-generation/dev-random] This means that no userspace daemon, such as rngd from rng-tools, is needed to do that job.
[src:secure-random-generation/dev-random] The entropy pool can be improved by programs like timer_entropyd, haveged, randomsound etc.
[src:secure-random-generation/dev-random] With rng-tools, hardware random number generators like *Entropy Key, etc.* can write to /dev/random.
[src:secure-random-generation/dev-random] The diehard tests programs diehard, dieharder and ent can test these random number generators.
[src:secure-random-generation/dev-random] Bernstein published a critique of how Linux mixes different sources of entropy.
[src:secure-random-generation/dev-random] He outlines an attack in which one source of entropy capable of monitoring the other sources of entropy could modify its output to nullify the randomness of the other sources of entropy.
[src:secure-random-generation/dev-random] If the output of ⁠ $H(x,y,r)$ ⁠ is equal to the desired value, output *r* as *z*.
[src:secure-random-generation/dev-random] Bernstein estimated that an attacker would need to repeat ⁠ $H(x,y,r)$ ⁠ 16 times to compromise DSA and ECDSA, by causing the first four bits of the RNG output to be 0.
[src:secure-random-generation/dev-random] This is possible because Linux reseeds H on an ongoing basis instead of using a single high quality seed.
[src:secure-random-generation/dev-random] Bernstein also argues that entropy injection is pointless once the CSPRNG has been initialized.
[src:secure-random-generation/dev-random] Donenfeld offered a new design of the Linux entropy pool infrastructure.
[src:secure-random-generation/dev-random] Donenfeld reported that the old pool, consisting of a single 4096-bit LFSR is vulnerable to two attacks: (1) an attacker can undo the effect of a known input; (2) if the whole pool's state is leaked, an attacker can set all bits in the pool to zero.
[src:secure-random-generation/dev-random] His new design, which is faster and safer, uses the blake2s hash function for mixing a 256-bit pool.
[src:secure-random-generation/dev-random] The FreeBSD operating system provides a /dev/urandom link to /dev/random.
[src:secure-random-generation/dev-random] FreeBSD's PRNG (Fortuna) reseeds regularly, and does not attempt to estimate entropy.
[src:secure-random-generation/dev-random] On a system with small amount of network and disk activity, reseeding is done after a fraction of a second.
[src:secure-random-generation/dev-random] DragonFly BSD inherited FreeBSD's random device files when it was forked.
[src:secure-random-generation/dev-random] Since OpenBSD 5.1 (May 1, 2012) /dev/random and /dev/arandom uses arc4random, a CSPRNG function based on RC4.
[src:secure-random-generation/dev-random] The function was changed to use the stronger ChaCha20 with OpenBSD 5.5 (May 1, 2014).
[src:secure-random-generation/dev-random] The system automatically uses hardware random number generators (such as those provided on some Intel PCI hubs) if they are available, through the OpenBSD Cryptographic Framework. /dev/arandom was removed in OpenBSD 6.3 (April 15, 2018).
[src:secure-random-generation/dev-random] NetBSD's implementation of the legacy `arc4random()` API has been switched over to ChaCha20 as well.
[src:secure-random-generation/dev-random] All Apple OSes have moved to Fortuna since at least December 2019, possibly earlier.
[src:secure-random-generation/dev-random] Multiple entropy sources such as the secure enclave RNG, boot phase timing jitter, hardware interrupt (timing assumed) are used.
[src:secure-random-generation/dev-random] RDSEED/RDRAND is used on Intel-based Macs that support it.
[src:secure-random-generation/dev-random] Seed (entropy) data is also stored for subsequent reboots.
[src:secure-random-generation/dev-random] Prior to the change, macOS and iOS used 160-bit Yarrow based on SHA-1.
[src:secure-random-generation/dev-random] There is no difference between /dev/random and /dev/urandom; both behave identically.
[src:secure-random-generation/dev-random] /dev/random and /dev/urandom are also available on Solaris, NetBSD, Tru64 UNIX 5.1B, AIX 5.2 and HP-UX 11i v2.
[src:secure-random-generation/dev-random] As with FreeBSD, AIX implements its own Yarrow-based design, however AIX uses considerably fewer entropy sources than the standard /dev/random implementation and stops refilling the pool when it thinks it contains enough entropy.
[src:secure-random-generation/dev-random] In Windows NT, similar functionality is delivered by ksecdd.sys, but reading the special file \Device\KsecDD does not work as in UNIX.
[src:secure-random-generation/dev-random] The documented methods to generate cryptographically random bytes are CryptGenRandom and RtlGenRandom.
[src:secure-random-generation/dev-random] Windows PowerShell provides access to a cryptographically secure pseudorandom number generator via the Get-SecureRandom cmdlet.
[src:secure-random-generation/entropy-computing] In computing, **entropy** is the randomness collected by an operating system or application for use in cryptography or other uses that require random data.
[src:secure-random-generation/entropy-computing] This randomness is often collected from hardware sources (variance in fan noise or HDD), either pre-existing ones such as mouse movements or specially provided randomness generators.
[src:secure-random-generation/entropy-computing] A lack of entropy can have a negative impact on performance and security.
[src:secure-random-generation/entropy-computing] The Linux kernel generates entropy from keyboard timings, mouse movements, and integrated drive electronics (IDE) timings and makes the random character data available to other operating system processes through the special files /dev/random and /dev/urandom.
[src:secure-random-generation/entropy-computing] This capability was introduced in Linux version 1.3.30.
[src:secure-random-generation/entropy-computing] There are some Linux kernel patches allowing one to use more entropy sources.
[src:secure-random-generation/entropy-computing] The audio_entropyd project, which is included in some operating systems such as Fedora, allows audio data to be used as an entropy source.
[src:secure-random-generation/entropy-computing] Also available are video_entropyd, which calculates random data from a video-source and entropybroker, which includes these three and can be used to distribute the entropy data to systems not capable of running any of these (e.g. virtual machines).
[src:secure-random-generation/entropy-computing] Furthermore, one can use the HAVEGE algorithm through haveged to pool entropy.
[src:secure-random-generation/entropy-computing] In some systems, network interrupts can be used as an entropy source as well.
[src:secure-random-generation/entropy-computing] OpenBSD has integrated cryptography as one of its main goals and has always worked on increasing its entropy for encryption but also for randomising many parts of the OS, including various internal operations of its kernel.
[src:secure-random-generation/entropy-computing] Around 2011, two of the random devices were dropped and linked into a single source as it could produce hundreds of megabytes per second of high quality random data on an average system.
[src:secure-random-generation/entropy-computing] This significantly reduced the likelihood of depletion of random data by userland programs on OpenBSD once sufficient entropy had been gathered.
[src:secure-random-generation/entropy-computing] A driver ported from the Linux kernel has been made available for the Hurd kernel.
[src:secure-random-generation/entropy-computing] /dev/random and /dev/urandom have been available as Sun packages or patches for Solaris since Solaris 2.6, and have been a standard feature since Solaris 9.
[src:secure-random-generation/entropy-computing] As of Solaris 10, administrators can remove existing entropy sources or define new ones via the kernel-level cryptographic framework.
[src:secure-random-generation/entropy-computing] A 3rd-party kernel module implementing /dev/random is also available for releases dating back to Solaris 2.4.
[src:secure-random-generation/entropy-computing] There is a software package for OS/2 that allows software processes to retrieve random data.
[src:secure-random-generation/entropy-computing] Microsoft Windows releases newer than Windows 95 use CryptoAPI to gather entropy in a manner similar to the Linux kernel's /dev/random.
[src:secure-random-generation/entropy-computing] Windows's CryptoAPI uses the binary registry key *HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\SOFTWARE\Microsoft\Cryptography\RNG\Seed* to store a seeded value from all of its entropy sources.
[src:secure-random-generation/entropy-computing] Because CryptoAPI is closed-source, some free and open source software applications running on the Windows platform use other measures to get randomness.
[src:secure-random-generation/entropy-computing] For example, GnuPG, as of version 1.06, uses a variety of sources such as the number of free bytes in memory that combined with a random seed generates desired randomness it needs.
[src:secure-random-generation/entropy-computing] Programmers using CAPI can get entropy by calling CAPI's CryptGenRandom(), after properly initializing it.
[src:secure-random-generation/entropy-computing] CryptoAPI was deprecated from Windows Vista and higher.
[src:secure-random-generation/entropy-computing] New API is called Cryptography API: Next Generation (CNG).
[src:secure-random-generation/entropy-computing] Windows's CNG uses the binary registry key *HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\SYSTEM\RNG\Seed* to store a seeded value.
[src:secure-random-generation/entropy-computing] Embedded systems may have difficulty gathering sufficient entropy, as they are often simple devices with short boot times, and key generation operations that require sufficient entropy are often one of the first things a system may do.
[src:secure-random-generation/entropy-computing] Common entropy sources may not exist on these devices, or may not have been active long enough during boot to generate sufficient entropy.
[src:secure-random-generation/entropy-computing] Embedded devices often lack rotating disk drives, human interface devices, and even fans, and the network interface, if any, will not have been active for long enough to provide much entropy.
[src:secure-random-generation/entropy-computing] Lacking easy access to entropy, some devices may use hard-coded keys to seed random generators, or seed random generators from easily guessed unique identifiers such as the device's MAC address.
[src:secure-random-generation/entropy-computing] A simple study demonstrated the widespread use of weak keys by finding many embedded systems such as routers using the same keys.
[src:secure-random-generation/entropy-computing] It was thought that the number of weak keys found would have been far higher if simple and often attacker determinable one-time unique identifiers had not been incorporated into the entropy of some of these systems.
[src:secure-random-generation/entropy-computing] A true random number generator (TRNG) can be a (de)central service.
[src:secure-random-generation/entropy-computing] One example of a centralized system where a random number can be acquired is the *randomness beacon service* from the National Institute of Standards and Technology.
[src:secure-random-generation/entropy-computing] The Cardano platform uses the participants of their decentralized proof-of-stake protocol to generate random numbers.
[src:secure-random-generation/entropy-computing] There are some software packages that allow one to use a userspace process to gather random characters, exactly what /dev/random does, such as EGD, the Entropy Gathering Daemon.
[src:secure-random-generation/entropy-computing] Modern CPUs and hardware often feature integrated generators that can provide high-quality and high-speed entropy to operating systems.
[src:secure-random-generation/entropy-computing] On systems based on the Linux kernel, one can read the entropy generated from such a device through /dev/hw_random.
[src:secure-random-generation/entropy-computing] There are some companies manufacturing entropy generation devices, and some of them are shipped with drivers for Linux.
[src:secure-random-generation/entropy-computing] This is especially useful on headless systems that have no other sources of entropy.
[src:secure-random-generation/entropy-computing] System administrators, especially those supervising Internet servers, have to ensure that the server processes will not halt because of entropy depletion.
[src:secure-random-generation/entropy-computing] The entropy pool size in Linux is viewable through the file */proc/sys/kernel/random/entropy_avail* and should generally be at least 2000 bits (out of a maximum of 4096).
[src:secure-random-generation/entropy-computing] Administrators responsible for systems that have low or zero entropy should not attempt to use /dev/urandom as a substitute for /dev/random as this may cause SSL/TLS connections to have lower-grade encryption.
[src:secure-random-generation/entropy-computing] Some software systems change their Diffie-Hellman keys often, and this may in some cases help a server to continue functioning normally even with an entropy bottleneck.
[src:secure-random-generation/entropy-computing] On servers with low entropy, a process can appear hung when it is waiting for random characters to appear in /dev/random (on Linux-based systems).
[src:secure-random-generation/entropy-computing] For example, there was a known problem in Debian that caused exim4 to hang in some cases because of this.
[src:secure-random-generation/entropy-computing] Entropy sources can be used for keyboard timing attacks.
[src:secure-random-generation/entropy-computing] Entropy can affect the cryptography (TLS/SSL) of a server: If a server fails to use a proper source of randomness, the keys generated by the server will be insecure.
[src:secure-random-generation/entropy-computing] In some cases a cracker (malicious attacker) can guess some bits of entropy from the output of a pseudorandom number generator (PRNG), and this happens when not enough entropy is introduced into the PRNG.
[src:secure-random-generation/entropy-computing] Commonly used entropy sources include the mouse, keyboard, and IDE timings, but there are other potential sources.
[src:secure-random-generation/entropy-computing] For example, one could collect entropy from the computer's microphone, or by building a sensor to measure the air turbulence inside a disk drive.
[src:secure-random-generation/entropy-computing] For Unix/BSD derivatives there exists a USB based solution that utilizes an ARM Cortex CPU for filtering / securing the bit stream generated by two entropy generator sources in the system.
[src:secure-random-generation/entropy-computing] Cloudflare uses an image feed from a rack of 80 lava lamps as an additional source of entropy.
[src:secure-random-generation/hardware-random-number-generator] Many natural phenomena generate low-level, statistically random "noise" signals, including thermal and shot noise, jitter and metastability of electronic circuits, Brownian motion, and atmospheric noise.
[src:secure-random-generation/hardware-random-number-generator] Researchers also used the photoelectric effect, involving a beam splitter, other quantum phenomena, and even nuclear decay (due to practical considerations the latter, as well as the atmospheric noise, is not viable except for fairly restricted applications or online distribution services).
[src:secure-random-generation/hardware-random-number-generator] While "classical" (non-quantum) phenomena are not truly random, an unpredictable physical system is usually acceptable as a source of randomness, so the qualifiers "true" and "physical" are used interchangeably.
[src:secure-random-generation/hardware-random-number-generator] A hardware random number generator is expected to output near-perfect random numbers ("full entropy").
[src:secure-random-generation/hardware-random-number-generator] Hardware random number generators generally produce only a limited number of random bits per second.
[src:secure-random-generation/hardware-random-number-generator] In order to increase the available output data rate, they are often used to generate the "seed" for a faster PRNG.
[src:secure-random-generation/hardware-random-number-generator] PRNG also helps with the noise source "anonymization" (whitening out the noise source identifying characteristics) and entropy extraction.
[src:secure-random-generation/hardware-random-number-generator] With a proper PRNG algorithm selected (cryptographically secure pseudorandom number generator, CSPRNG), the combination can satisfy the requirements of Federal Information Processing Standards and Common Criteria standards.
[src:secure-random-generation/hardware-random-number-generator] Hardware random number generators can be used in any application that needs randomness.
[src:secure-random-generation/hardware-random-number-generator] However, in many scientific applications additional cost and complexity of a TRNG (when compared with pseudo random number generators) provide no meaningful benefits.
[src:secure-random-generation/hardware-random-number-generator] TRNGs have additional drawbacks for data science and statistical applications: impossibility to re-run a series of numbers unless they are stored, reliance on an analog physical entity can obscure the failure of the source.
[src:secure-random-generation/hardware-random-number-generator] The TRNGs therefore are primarily used in the applications where their unpredictability and the impossibility to re-run the sequence of numbers are crucial to the success of the implementation: in cryptography and gambling machines.
[src:secure-random-generation/hardware-random-number-generator] The major use for hardware random number generators is in the field of data encryption, for example to create random cryptographic keys and nonces needed to encrypt and sign data.
[src:secure-random-generation/hardware-random-number-generator] 2. backward secrecy protects the "opposite direction": knowledge of the output and internal state in the future should not divulge the preceding data.
[src:secure-random-generation/hardware-random-number-generator] A typical way to fulfill these requirements is to use a TRNG to seed a cryptographically secure pseudorandom number generator.
[src:secure-random-generation/hardware-random-number-generator] Physical devices were used to generate random numbers for thousands of years, primarily for gambling.
[src:secure-random-generation/hardware-random-number-generator] Dice in particular have been known for more than 5000 years (found on locations in modern Iraq and Iran), and flipping a coin (thus producing a random bit) dates at least to the times of ancient Rome.
[src:secure-random-generation/hardware-random-number-generator] The first documented use of a physical random number generator for scientific purposes was by Francis Galton (1890).
[src:secure-random-generation/hardware-random-number-generator] He devised a way to sample a probability distribution using a common gambling die.
[src:secure-random-generation/hardware-random-number-generator] In addition to the top digit, Galton also looked at the face of a die closest to him, thus creating 6*4 = 24 outcomes (about 4.6 bits of randomness).
[src:secure-random-generation/hardware-random-number-generator] Kendall and Babington-Smith (1938) used a fast-rotating 10-sector disk that was illuminated by periodic bursts of light.
[src:secure-random-generation/hardware-random-number-generator] The sampling was done by a human who wrote the number under the light beam onto a pad.
[src:secure-random-generation/hardware-random-number-generator] The device was utilized to produce a 100,000-digit random number table (at the time such tables were used for statistical experiments, like PRNG nowadays).
[src:secure-random-generation/hardware-random-number-generator] On 29 April 1947, the RAND Corporation began generating random digits with an "electronic roulette wheel", consisting of a random frequency pulse source of about 100,000 pulses per second gated once per second with a constant frequency pulse and fed into a five-bit binary counter.
[src:secure-random-generation/hardware-random-number-generator] Douglas Aircraft built the equipment, implementing Cecil Hasting's suggestion (RAND P-113) for a noise source (most likely the well known behavior of the 6D4 miniature gas thyratron tube, when placed in a magnetic field).
[src:secure-random-generation/hardware-random-number-generator] Twenty of the 32 possible counter values were mapped onto the 10 decimal digits and the other 12 counter values were discarded.
[src:secure-random-generation/hardware-random-number-generator] The results of a long run from the RAND machine, filtered and tested, were converted into a table, which originally existed only as a deck of punched cards, but was later published in 1955 as a book, 50 rows of 50 digits on each page (*A Million Random Digits with 100,000 Normal Deviates*).
[src:secure-random-generation/hardware-random-number-generator] The RAND table was a significant breakthrough in delivering random numbers because such a large and carefully prepared table had never before been available.
[src:secure-random-generation/hardware-random-number-generator] It has been a useful source for simulations, modeling, and for deriving the arbitrary constants in cryptographic algorithms to demonstrate that the constants had not been selected maliciously ("nothing up my sleeve numbers").
[src:secure-random-generation/hardware-random-number-generator] Since the early 1950s, research into TRNGs has been highly active, with thousands of research works published and about 2000 patents granted by 2017.
[src:secure-random-generation/hardware-random-number-generator] Multiple different TRNG designs were proposed over time with a large variety of noise sources and digitization techniques ("harvesting").
[src:secure-random-generation/hardware-random-number-generator] Noise-based RNGs generally follow the same outline: the source of a noise generator is fed into a comparator.
[src:secure-random-generation/hardware-random-number-generator] If the voltage is above threshold, the comparator output is 1, otherwise 0.
[src:secure-random-generation/hardware-random-number-generator] The random bit value is latched using a flip-flop.
[src:secure-random-generation/hardware-random-number-generator] The idea of chaos-based noise stems from the use of a complex system that is hard to characterize by observing its behavior over time.
[src:secure-random-generation/hardware-random-number-generator] For example, lasers can be put into (undesirable in other applications) chaos mode with chaotically fluctuating power, with power detected using a photodiode and sampled by a comparator.
[src:secure-random-generation/hardware-random-number-generator] The design can be quite small, as all photonics elements can be integrated on-chip.
[src:secure-random-generation/hardware-random-number-generator] The TRNGs based on a free-running oscillator (FRO) typically utilize one or more ring oscillators (ROs), outputs of which are sampled using yet another clock.
[src:secure-random-generation/hardware-random-number-generator] Since inverters forming the RO can be thought of as amplifiers with a very large gain, an FRO output exhibits very fast oscillations in phase and frequency domains.
[src:secure-random-generation/hardware-random-number-generator] The FRO-based TRNGs are very popular due to their use of the standard digital logic despite issues with randomness proofs and chip-to-chip variability.
[src:secure-random-generation/hardware-random-number-generator] Quantum random number generation technology is well established with 8 commercial **quantum random number generator** (**QRNG**) products offered before 2017.
[src:secure-random-generation/hardware-random-number-generator] To reduce costs and increase robustness of quantum random number generators, online services have been implemented.
[src:secure-random-generation/hardware-random-number-generator] A plurality of quantum random number generators designs are inherently untestable and thus can be manipulated by adversaries.
[src:secure-random-generation/hardware-random-number-generator] Mannalath et al. call these designs "trusted" in a sense that they can only operate in a fully controlled, trusted environment.
[src:secure-random-generation/hardware-random-number-generator] The failure of a TRNG can be quite complex and subtle, necessitating validation of not just the results (the output bit stream), but of the unpredictability of the entropy source.
[src:secure-random-generation/hardware-random-number-generator] Hardware random number generators should be constantly monitored for proper operation to protect against the entropy source degradation due to natural causes and deliberate attacks.
[src:secure-random-generation/hardware-random-number-generator] FIPS Pub 140-2 and NIST Special Publication 800-90B define tests which can be used for this.
[src:secure-random-generation/hardware-random-number-generator] *adaptive proportion test* verifies that any random digit does not occur too frequently in the data stream (low bias).
[src:secure-random-generation/hardware-random-number-generator] For bit-oriented entropy sources that means that the count of 1s and 0s in the bit stream is approximately the same.
[src:secure-random-generation/hardware-random-number-generator] Just as with other components of a cryptography system, a cryptographic random number generator should be designed to resist certain attacks.
[src:secure-random-generation/hardware-random-number-generator] Defending against these attacks is difficult without a hardware entropy source.
[src:secure-random-generation/hardware-random-number-generator] The physical processes in HRNG introduce new attack surfaces.
[src:secure-random-generation/hardware-random-number-generator] For example, a free-running oscillator-based TRNG can be attacked using a frequency injection.
[src:secure-random-generation/hardware-random-number-generator] There are mathematical techniques for estimating the entropy of a sequence of symbols.
[src:secure-random-generation/hardware-random-number-generator] None are so reliable that their estimates can be fully relied upon; there are always assumptions which may be very difficult to confirm.
[src:secure-random-generation/hardware-random-number-generator] These are useful for determining if there is enough entropy in a seed pool, for example, but they cannot, in general, distinguish between a true random source and a pseudorandom generator.
[src:secure-random-generation/hardware-random-number-generator] This problem is avoided by the conservative use of hardware entropy sources.
[src:secure-random-generation/random-number-generation] Various applications of randomness have led to the development of different methods for generating random data.
[src:secure-random-generation/random-number-generation] Some of these have existed since ancient times, including well-known examples like the rolling of dice, coin flipping, the shuffling of playing cards, the use of yarrow stalks (for divination) in the I Ching, as well as countless other techniques.
[src:secure-random-generation/random-number-generation] Because of the mechanical nature of these techniques, generating large quantities of sufficiently random numbers (important in statistics) required much work and time.
[src:secure-random-generation/random-number-generation] Thus, results would sometimes be collected and distributed as random number tables.
[src:secure-random-generation/random-number-generation] Several computational methods for pseudorandom number generation exist.
[src:secure-random-generation/random-number-generation] All fall short of the goal of true randomness, although they may meet, with varying success, some of the statistical tests for randomness intended to measure how unpredictable their results are (that is, to what degree their patterns are discernible).
[src:secure-random-generation/random-number-generation] This generally makes them unusable for applications such as cryptography.
[src:secure-random-generation/random-number-generation] However, carefully designed *cryptographically secure pseudorandom number generators* (CSPRNGS) also exist, with special features specifically designed for use in cryptography.
[src:secure-random-generation/random-number-generation] Random number generators have applications in gambling, statistical sampling, computer simulation, cryptography, completely randomized design, and other areas where producing an unpredictable result is desirable.
[src:secure-random-generation/random-number-generation] Generally, in applications having unpredictability as the paramount feature, such as in security applications, hardware generators are generally preferred over pseudorandom algorithms, where feasible.
[src:secure-random-generation/random-number-generation] Pseudorandom number generators are very useful in developing Monte Carlo-method simulations, as debugging is facilitated by the ability to run the same sequence of random numbers again by starting from the same *random seed*.
[src:secure-random-generation/random-number-generation] They are also used in cryptography – so long as the *seed* is secret.
[src:secure-random-generation/random-number-generation] The sender and receiver can generate the same set of numbers automatically to use as keys.
[src:secure-random-generation/random-number-generation] The generation of pseudorandom numbers is an important and common task in computer programming.
[src:secure-random-generation/random-number-generation] While cryptography and certain numerical algorithms require a very high degree of *apparent* randomness, many other operations only need a modest amount of unpredictability.
[src:secure-random-generation/random-number-generation] Some simple examples might be presenting a user with a "random quote of the day", or determining which way a computer-controlled adversary might move in a computer game.
[src:secure-random-generation/random-number-generation] Weaker forms of *randomness* are used in hash algorithms and in creating amortized searching and sorting algorithms.
[src:secure-random-generation/random-number-generation] Some applications that appear at first sight to be suitable for randomization are in fact not quite so simple.
[src:secure-random-generation/random-number-generation] For instance, a system that "randomly" selects music tracks for a background music system must only *appear* random, and may even have ways to control the selection of music: a truly random system would have no restriction on the same item appearing two or three times in succession.
[src:secure-random-generation/random-number-generation] There are two principal methods used to generate random numbers.
[src:secure-random-generation/random-number-generation] The first method measures some physical phenomenon that is expected to be random and then compensates for possible biases in the measurement process.
[src:secure-random-generation/random-number-generation] Example sources include measuring atmospheric noise, thermal noise, and other external electromagnetic and quantum phenomena.
[src:secure-random-generation/random-number-generation] For example, cosmic background radiation or radioactive decay as measured over short timescales represent sources of natural entropy (as a measure of unpredictability or surprise of the number generation process).
[src:secure-random-generation/random-number-generation] The speed at which entropy can be obtained from natural sources is dependent on the underlying physical phenomena being measured.
[src:secure-random-generation/random-number-generation] Thus, sources of naturally occurring *true* entropy are said to be blocking – they are rate-limited until enough entropy is harvested to meet the demand.
[src:secure-random-generation/random-number-generation] On some Unix-like systems, including most Linux distributions, the pseudo device file /dev/random will block until sufficient entropy is harvested from the environment.
[src:secure-random-generation/random-number-generation] Due to this blocking behavior, large bulk reads from /dev/random, such as filling a hard disk drive with random bits, can often be slow on systems that use this type of entropy source.
[src:secure-random-generation/random-number-generation] The second method uses computational algorithms that can produce long sequences of apparently random results, which are in fact completely determined by a shorter initial value, known as a seed value or key.
[src:secure-random-generation/random-number-generation] As a result, the entire seemingly random sequence can be reproduced if the seed value is known.
[src:secure-random-generation/random-number-generation] This type of random number generator is often called a pseudorandom number generator.
[src:secure-random-generation/random-number-generation] This type of generator typically does not rely on sources of naturally occurring entropy, though it may be periodically seeded by natural sources.
[src:secure-random-generation/random-number-generation] This generator type is non-blocking, so they are not rate-limited by an external event, making large bulk reads a possibility.
[src:secure-random-generation/random-number-generation] Standard cryptographic designs take a hybrid approach, using randomness harvested from natural sources to seed a cryptographically secure pseudorandom number generators (CSPRNGs).
[src:secure-random-generation/random-number-generation] The earliest methods for generating random numbers, such as dice, coin flipping and roulette wheels, are still used today, mainly in games and gambling, as they tend to be too slow for most applications in statistics and cryptography.
[src:secure-random-generation/random-number-generation] For performance and security reasons, most random number generators use PRNGs in their construction (this architecture is actually mandated in the industrial standards like NIST SP 800-90A).
[src:secure-random-generation/random-number-generation] A pseudorandom number generator (PRNG), also known as a deterministic random bit generator (DRBG), is an algorithm for generating a sequence of numbers whose properties approximate the properties of sequences of random numbers.
[src:secure-random-generation/random-number-generation] The PRNG-generated sequence is not truly random, because it is completely determined by an initial value, called the PRNG's *seed* (which may include truly random values).
[src:secure-random-generation/random-number-generation] Although sequences that are closer to truly random can be generated using hardware random number generators, *pseudorandom number generators* are important in practice for their speed in number generation and their reproducibility.
[src:secure-random-generation/random-number-generation] PRNGs are central in applications such as simulations (e.g. for the Monte Carlo method), electronic games (e.g. for procedural generation), and cryptography.
[src:secure-random-generation/random-number-generation] Cryptographic applications require the output not to be predictable from earlier outputs, and more elaborate algorithms, which do not inherit the linearity of simpler PRNGs, are needed.
[src:secure-random-generation/random-number-generation] Good statistical properties are a central requirement for the output of a PRNG.
[src:secure-random-generation/random-number-generation] In general, careful mathematical analysis is required to have any confidence that a PRNG generates numbers that are sufficiently close to random to suit the intended use.
[src:secure-random-generation/random-number-generation] Random number generation may also be performed by humans, in the form of collecting various inputs from end users and using them as a randomization source.
[src:secure-random-generation/random-number-generation] However, most studies find that human subjects have some degree of non-randomness when attempting to produce a random sequence of e.g., digits or letters.
[src:secure-random-generation/random-number-generation] They may alternate too much between choices when compared to a good random generator; thus, this approach is not widely used.
[src:secure-random-generation/random-number-generation] However, for the very reason that humans perform poorly in this task, human random number generation can be used as a tool to gain insights into brain functions otherwise not accessible.
[src:secure-random-generation/random-number-generation] Even given a source of plausible random numbers (perhaps from a quantum mechanically based hardware generator), obtaining numbers which are completely unbiased takes care.
[src:secure-random-generation/random-number-generation] In addition, behavior of these generators often changes with temperature, power supply voltage, the age of the device, or other outside interference.
[src:secure-random-generation/random-number-generation] Generated random numbers are sometimes subjected to statistical tests before use to ensure that the underlying source is still working, and then post-processed to improve their statistical properties.
[src:secure-random-generation/random-number-generation] An example would be the TRNG9803 hardware random number generator, which uses an entropy measurement as a hardware test, and then post-processes the random sequence with a shift register stream cipher.
[src:secure-random-generation/random-number-generation] It is generally hard to use statistical tests to validate the generated random numbers.
[src:secure-random-generation/random-number-generation] Wang and Nicol proposed a distance-based statistical testing technique that is used to identify the weaknesses of several random generators.
[src:secure-random-generation/random-number-generation] Li and Wang proposed a method of testing random numbers based on laser chaotic entropy sources using Brownian motion properties.
[src:secure-random-generation/random-number-generation] Statistical tests are also used to give confidence that the post-processed final output from a random number generator is truly unbiased, with numerous randomness test suites being developed.
[src:secure-random-generation/random-number-generation] Most random number generators natively work with integers or individual bits, so an extra step is required to arrive at the *canonical* uniform distribution between 0 and 1.
[src:secure-random-generation/random-number-generation] The implementation is not as trivial as dividing the integer by its maximum possible value.
[src:secure-random-generation/random-number-generation] The nature of floating-point math itself means there exists more precision the closer the number is to zero.
[src:secure-random-generation/random-number-generation] This extra precision is usually not used due to the sheer number of bits required.
[src:secure-random-generation/random-number-generation] Rounding error in division may bias the result.
[src:secure-random-generation/random-number-generation] At worst, a supposedly excluded bound may be drawn contrary to expectations based on real-number math.
[src:secure-random-generation/random-number-generation] The mainstream algorithm, used by OpenJDK, Rust, and NumPy, is described in a proposal for C++'s STL.
[src:secure-random-generation/random-number-generation] It does not use the extra precision and suffers from bias only in the last bit due to rounding half to even.
[src:secure-random-generation/random-number-generation] Other numeric concerns are warranted when shifting this *canonical* uniform distribution to a different range.
[src:secure-random-generation/random-number-generation] A proposed method for the Swift programming language claims to use the full precision everywhere.
[src:secure-random-generation/random-number-generation] Uniformly distributed integers are commonly used in algorithms such as the Fisher–Yates shuffle.
[src:secure-random-generation/random-number-generation] Again, a naive implementation may induce a modulo bias into the result, so more involved algorithms must be used.
[src:secure-random-generation/random-number-generation] A method that nearly never performs division was described in 2018 by Daniel Lemire, with the current state-of-the-art being the arithmetic encoding-inspired 2021 "optimal algorithm" by Stephen Canon of Apple Inc.
[src:secure-random-generation/random-number-generation] Most 0 to 1 RNGs include 0 but exclude 1, while others include or exclude both.
[src:secure-random-generation/random-number-generation] Given a source of uniform random numbers, there are a couple of methods to create a new random source that corresponds to a probability density function.
[src:secure-random-generation/random-number-generation] One method called the inversion method, involves integrating up to an area greater than or equal to the random number (which should be generated between 0 and 1 for proper distributions).
[src:secure-random-generation/random-number-generation] A second method called the acceptance-rejection method, involves choosing an x and y value and testing whether the function of x is greater than the y value.
[src:secure-random-generation/random-number-generation] Otherwise, the x value is rejected and the algorithm tries again.
[src:secure-random-generation/random-number-generation] As an example for rejection sampling, to generate a pair of statistically independent standard normally distributed random numbers (*x*, *y*), one may first generate the polar coordinates (*r*, *θ*), where *r*2~χ22 and *θ*~UNIFORM(0,2π) (see Box–Muller transform).
[src:secure-random-generation/random-number-generation] The outputs of multiple independent RNGs can be combined (for example, using a bit-wise XOR operation) to provide a combined RNG at least as good as the best RNG used.
[src:secure-random-generation/random-number-generation] This is referred to as software whitening.
[src:secure-random-generation/random-number-generation] Computational and hardware random number generators are sometimes combined to reflect the benefits of both kinds.
[src:secure-random-generation/random-number-generation] Computational random number generators can typically generate pseudorandom numbers much faster than physical generators, while physical generators can generate true randomness.
[src:secure-random-generation/random-number-generation] Some computations making use of a random number generator can be summarized as the computation of a total or average value, such as the computation of integrals by the Monte Carlo method.
[src:secure-random-generation/random-number-generation] For such problems, it may be possible to find a more accurate solution by the use of so-called low-discrepancy sequences, also called quasirandom numbers.
[src:secure-random-generation/random-number-generation] Such sequences have a definite pattern that fills in gaps evenly, qualitatively speaking; a truly random sequence may, and usually does, leave larger gaps.
[src:secure-random-generation/random-number-generation] Since much cryptography depends on a cryptographically secure random number generator for key and cryptographic nonce generation, if a random number generator can be made predictable, it can be used as backdoor by an attacker to break the encryption.
[src:secure-random-generation/random-number-generation] The NSA is reported to have inserted a backdoor into the NIST certified cryptographically secure pseudorandom number generator Dual EC DRBG.
[src:secure-random-generation/random-number-generation] If for example an SSL connection is created using this random number generator, then according to Matthew Green it would allow NSA to determine the state of the random number generator, and thereby eventually be able to read all data sent over the SSL connection.
[src:secure-random-generation/random-number-generation] Even though it was apparent that Dual_EC_DRBG was a very poor and possibly backdoored pseudorandom number generator long before the NSA backdoor was confirmed in 2013, it had seen significant usage in practice until 2013, for example by the prominent security company RSA Security.
[src:secure-random-generation/random-number-generation] There have subsequently been accusations that RSA Security knowingly inserted a NSA backdoor into its products, possibly as part of the Bullrun program.
[src:secure-random-generation/random-number-generation] RSA has denied knowingly inserting a backdoor into its products.
[src:secure-random-generation/random-number-generation] It has also been theorized that hardware RNGs could be secretly modified to have less entropy than stated, which would make encryption using the hardware RNG susceptible to attack.
[src:secure-random-generation/random-number-generation] One such method that has been published works by modifying the dopant mask of the chip, which would be undetectable to optical reverse-engineering.
[src:secure-random-generation/random-number-generation] For example, for random number generation in Linux, it is seen as unacceptable to use Intel's RDRAND hardware RNG without mixing in the RDRAND output with other sources of entropy to counteract any backdoors in the hardware RNG, especially after the revelation of the NSA Bullrun program.
[src:secure-random-generation/random-number-generation] In 2010, a U.S. lottery draw was rigged by the information security director of the Multi-State Lottery Association (MUSL), who surreptitiously installed backdoor malware on the MUSL's secure RNG computer during routine maintenance.
[src:secure-random-generation/random-number-generation] During the hacks the man won a total amount of $16,500,000 over multiple years.
